=== TASK ===
# Checkout / Payment Completion

## Overview
Create a public-facing Checkout / Payment Completion experience for Roam Resort that enables guests to complete payments via Stripe links (Stripe Connect - Payment Links or hosted Stripe Checkout sessions) and then return to the platform to have the corresponding inquiry status updated by the concierge/admin workflow. This feature must support concierge-driven manual payment collection, robust webhook handling, secure redirection flows, and graceful user messaging for success/failure states. All UI, API, and data flows must be resilient to null/undefined values and guarded against non-array data, following the runtime safety rules provided.

---

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A public-facing Landing page that guests land on after following a Stripe payment link (hosted Stripe Checkout or Stripe Payment Link). The page serves as the bridge to Stripe’s hosted flow and then returns the guest to the Roam Resort platform with updated inquiry state.

Goals:
- Provide a clear, premium, editorial experience that communicates: “You are about to complete payment” and “You will be redirected back to Roam Resort after payment.”
- Present a concise inquiry summary (destination, dates, guests, inquiry reference) to reassure the guest of what they are paying for.
- Provide a safe, predictable path back to Roam Resort, including handling Stripe success and failure states.
- Offer a support CTA for payment issues (contact concierge, retry, or escalate).
- Automatically update the associated inquiry status on the platform when Stripe confirms payment (via webhooks or return query parameters).

Connected features:
- Manual Payment Collection (Stripe Connect - Payment Links): Admin creates Stripe payment links tied to inquiries; Stripe webhooks push payment state back to the platform to update status.
- Payment Result Handling: The page must gracefully interpret Stripe outcomes (success, canceled, incomplete) and reflect appropriate messaging and navigation.
- Redirection Bridge: After payment, guest is guided back to Roam Resort with context to update the internal inquiry.

UI elements and visual guidance:
- Top header with brand feel, breadcrumb or context indicator (Inquiry #, Destination).
- Hero/summary section: Large message, perhaps a subtle confirmation header indicating Stripe flow.
- Inquiry Summary Card: Key details (destination, dates, guests, inquiry reference), with muted, editorial styling.
- Redirect/Progress notice: Indicator that user will be redirected to Roam’s site after Stripe completes payment.
- Payment status area: If redirected with status parameters, show explicit success/failure messages, actions to take, and a link back to the inquiry.
- Support section: Clear CTA to contact concierge or support if payment doesn’t complete.
- Footer: Basic Roam Resort footer with policy links.

Important: The design must adhere to the Visual Style and UI/UX guidelines provided (luxury editorial aesthetic, warm tones, balanced typography, generous spacing, and accessible controls).

---

## Components to Build
- CheckoutBridgePage (Frontend)
  - Props/state: Stripe session id, inquiryId, status query params (e.g., payment_intent_status), redirectUrl.
  - Subcomponents:
    - BrandHeader
    - InquirySummaryCard
    - RedirectNotice
    - StatusPanel (success/failure handling based on query parameters or webhook-passed state)
    - SupportCTASection
  - Behavior:
    - Show Stripe redirect messaging, summarize inquiry, and provide a path to Stripe flow.
    - Read status from query params or from a webhook-ping payload stored in session or via a short-lived verification endpoint.
    - Safe rendering with guards for missing data; use data ?? [] patterns where arrays are involved.
- StripeWebhookListener (Backend)
  - Endpoint: POST /webhooks/stripe
  - Verifies Stripe signature, parses events (checkout.session.completed, payment_intent.succeeded, payment_intent.payment_failed, etc.).
  - Maps Stripe payment state to internal Inquiry status, updates DB, triggers notifications to guest/concierge if needed.
  - Safe handling for null data; uses Array.isArray guards when iterating.
- InquiryService (Backend)
  - Functions to update inquiry status, attach payment records, log internal notes.
- AdminPaymentLinkCreator (Backend/Admin)
  - Admin UI flow (behind auth) to create Stripe Payment Links or Checkout Sessions tied to an inquiry.
  - Stores mapping between inquiryId and Stripe payment link session URL.
- PaymentCompletionHandler (Backend)
  - When guest returns to Roam after Stripe flow, endpoint or client-side handler processes the return data, validates the payment state via Stripe or internal cache, and redirects to the appropriate in-app inquiry detail or support page.
- FrontendRouterGuard (Frontend)
  - Validates presence of necessary route params; if missing, redirects to a helpful fallback (inquiry list or landing page).
- Data Models (DB)
  - Inquiry: id, guestId, destinationId, dates, guests, status, paymentState, paymentLinkId, paymentLinkUrl, lastUpdated
  - PaymentLink: id, inquiryId, stripeCheckoutSessionId, stripePaymentLinkId, url, createdAt, expiresAt, status
  - PaymentEventLog: id, inquiryId, eventType, stripeEventId, payload, createdAt
- Utilities
  - SafeArrayUtil: to guard against non-arrays (e.g., (array ?? []).map(...))
  - Validation helpers: ensure required fields exist (destination, dates, guests)
  - Null-safe accessors and destructuring with defaults

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages/Routes:
  - /checkout/complete/:inquiryId?session_id=xxx&status=success|failed
  - /checkout/bridge/:inquiryId (public bridge when landing from Stripe)
  - In-app fallback: /inquiries/:inquiryId
- UI Components:
  - HeroWithSummary: large heading, message about Stripe flow, and a summary card.
  - InquirySummaryCard: robust rendering with guards; uses (inquiry?.destination?.name ?? "Destination") and similar defaults.
  - StatusBanner: shows success or failure state with appropriate messaging and actions.
  - SupportCard: contact options (email, chat, phone) with accessible controls.
  - CTA Button: bronze-gold (#A97C50) with hover state, uses disabled state when loading.
- Data Handling:
  - Always initialize arrays with proper defaults (e.g., useState<Inquiry[]>([]) is for lists; for single items: useState<Inquiry | null>(null)).
  - Guard against null/undefined when mapping lists (e.g., const items = (data ?? []) as any[]; items.map(...) guarded with Array.isArray(data)).
- Stripe integration:
  - The page should not attempt to perform Stripe operations directly; instead, it should present the Stripe-hosted flow and then expect return data. If the page is used as a bridge, display a clear message and provide a direct link to the Stripe session when appropriate.
- Routing and redirects:
  - After payment, Stripe redirects back with session_id or payment_intent, which the page uses (via webhook or API call) to determine final status.
  - If status=success, show a friendly success state and a button to navigate to the related inquiry detail page.
  - If status=failed, show a failure explanation and steps to retry via concierge or support.
- Security:
  - Validate query parameters server-side (or via a protected API) before rendering sensitive details.
  - Do not expose internal IDs in the client beyond what is necessary; use temporary tokens if needed.
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible; use ARIA labels and roles where appropriate.

### Backend
- Stripe Webhook Processing:
  - Validate webhook signatures with Stripe secret.
  - Handle events:
    - checkout.session.completed: mark related inquiry as Deposit Paid; store sessionId and related metadata.
    - payment_intent.succeeded: ensure inquiry payment state updated; set final status to Confirmed if appropriate.
    - payment_intent.payment_failed or checkout.session.async_payment_failed: flag as Payment Failed; notify guest/concierge.
  - Update database via InquiryService to reflect new state.
- Data Validation and Safety:
  - Ensure all DB writes guard against nulls; use data ?? [] patterns for arrays retrieved from DB.
  - Validate that inquiryId in webhook payload maps to an existing inquiry; if not, route to admin review or log for reconciliation.
- Admin API:
  - Create Payment Link: Admin endpoint to create Stripe Payment Link or Checkout Session for a given inquiryId.
  - Return payload includes: paymentLinkUrl, stripeSessionId, status.
- Payment Status Query API:
  - Endpoint to fetch latest payment state for an inquiry (used by frontend bridge page to render status after redirect).
- Security:
  - Authenticate admin routes; guests should not access admin endpoints.
  - Use role-based access controls to restrict data exposure.

### Integration
- Data Flow:
  - Concierge/admin creates a Stripe Payment Link for an inquiry (PaymentLink object stores stripe identifiers).
  - Guest lands on /checkout/bridge/:inquiryId, receives summary and a link to Stripe flow.
  - Stripe processes payment; Stripe sends webhook to /webhooks/stripe, updating Inquiry.paymentState and PaymentLink status.
  - Guest is redirected back to Roam; the frontend route /checkout/complete/:inquiryId uses backend API to fetch latest state and render success/failure messaging.
- Event Handling:
  - Webhook events update internal models; the frontend may poll briefly or use a session-based callback to display final status.
- Data Consistency:
  - All arrays are guarded; use (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks wherever mapping occurs.
  - All useState initializations for arrays = [] and for objects = null or appropriate defaults.

---

## User Experience Flow
1) Guest receives Stripe payment link via email or concierge-created link.
2) Guest lands on CheckoutBridgePage (public bridge) showing:
   - Stripe redirect messaging
   - Inquiry summary (destination, dates, guests, reference)
   - Clear CTA to proceed to Stripe checkout/link
   - Contact support if issues arise
3) Guest completes payment on Stripe-hosted page.
4) Stripe returns guest to Roam Resort via redirect or webhook fires:
   - If returning via redirect with status param, the CheckoutBridgePage or PaymentCompletionHandler shows a status banner (success or failure) and directs to the relevant Inquiry detail page or support.
   - If webhook, internal systems update the inquiry status automatically; guest is guided to a final status screen with a redirect to the inquiry.
5) Concierge/admin can view the updated inquiry in AdminPanel, with a new PaymentState and internal notes if needed; reconciliation can be performed offline if required.

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models
  - Inquiry: id (string), guestId, destinationId, startDate, endDate, guests (number), status (string), paymentState (string), paymentLinkId (string|null), paymentLinkUrl (string|null), lastUpdated (timestamp)
  - PaymentLink: id (string), inquiryId (string), stripeCheckoutSessionId (string|null), stripePaymentLinkId (string|null), url (string|null), createdAt (timestamp), expiresAt (timestamp|null), status (string)
  - PaymentEventLog: id (string), inquiryId (string), eventType (string), stripeEventId (string), payload (JSON), createdAt (timestamp)

- API Endpoints
  - POST /admin/payment-links
    - Body: { inquiryId: string, customerNote?: string }
    - Response: { paymentLinkUrl: string, stripeSessionId?: string, status: string }
  - GET /inquiries/:inquiryId/payment-status
    - Response: { inquiryId, paymentState, status, paymentLinkUrl, stripeSessionId }
  - POST /webhooks/stripe
    - Stripe webhook endpoint for all relevant events
  - GET /checkout/bridge/:inquiryId
    - Public bridge page data (requires no auth, but can verify inquiryId)
  - GET /checkout/complete/:inquiryId
    - Payment completion status data for UI rendering

- Security
  - Authenticate admin endpoints via JWT/OAuth; guest-facing endpoints require no authentication but should not leak sensitive data.
  - Validate incoming Stripe signatures in webhook handler.
  - Use CSRF protection for admin-only forms; public endpoints should rely on referer checks and tokens if necessary.

- Validation
  - For all inputs, implement validation with defaults:
    - const { inquiryId, … } = req.body ?? {};
    - Ensure inquiryId exists and maps to a valid Inquiry.
  - On frontend, safeguard against missing inquiry data:
    - const inquiry = data?.inquiry ?? null;
    - (inquiry?.guests ?? 0) > 0 as a check.
  - Access nested data safely: data?.destination?.name ?? "Destination".

- Runtime Safety Guidelines (Mandatory)
  - Supabase-like patterns: never assume data is an array; use data ?? [] when mapping.
  - Array methods guarded: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - useState initialization: useState<T[]>([]) for arrays; useState<Inquiry | null>(null) for single objects.
  - API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining: use obj?.property?.nested everywhere when handling API/db data.
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {};

